   Johnson and Ronald Reagan.  This analysis shows Johnson's establishment
   of the metaphor of the footrace to describe life in the United States
   and Reagan's attempt to contest this metaphor.  Johnson's rhetoric
   appealed to the notion of the ''starting line'' and the need for
   government to establish equal competitive conditions.  Reagan appealed
   to the ''runners'' and argued that individual competitors need to rely
   on athletic ''character'' rather than government to succeed.  It is
   argued that attention to the sport metaphor in public discourse as well
   as to the theoretical points raised in its analysis is needed in the
