AB The awarding of the 1992 Nobel Prize for Economics to Gary Becker draws
   attention to Becker's outstanding work in economics. At the same time,
   it draws attention to a new phenomenon, for which Becker himself is more
   responsible than anyone else: the use of basic principles of economics
   to address problems in sociology. Much of the work for which Becker is
   best known treats problems that are quite outside the field of economics
