AB Educators have long recognized the importance of teaching critical
   thinking skills in the college classroom.  A core group of sociology
   faculty members at a midwestern university introduced critical thinking
   into their introductory sociology courses as a specific instructional
   component.  In this paper we review the objectives of four instructional
   programs and the specific strategies these faculty members used in
   nurturing critical reasoning skills.  We developed a four-page
   questionnaire to assess the students' perceptions of these programs. 
   Overall the programs appear effective in the eyes of the students; 70
   percent believed they had adequate opportunities to develop their
   critical reasoning skills, and 62 percent reported an increase in those
   skills.  We discuss the findings from this project in terms of the
   relevance of critical thinking to the sociology curriculum.
